,"HSV-1 is the most common cause of genital herpes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSV-2 is the most common cause of genital herpes\u003C/strong\u003E, although HSV-1 can also cause genital infections. Genital herpes presents as vesicles on the genital mucous membranes and external genitalia that rapidly convert to superficial ulcerations with inflammatory infiltrate at the margins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSV-1 is the most common cause of genital herpes\u003C/strong\u003E - While HSV-1 can cause genital herpes, HSV-2 is more commonly associated with genital infections.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSV-2 typically causes painless genital ulcerations\u003C/strong\u003E - Genital herpes lesions are characteristically painful, not painless.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSV-2 infection rarely recurs after initial episode\u003C/strong\u003E - HSV-2 infection is known for its tendency to cause recurrent episodes, as the virus establishes latency in sensory ganglia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSV-2 cannot be transmitted to neonates during delivery\u003C/strong\u003E - HSV-2 can be transmitted to neonates during passage through the birth canal of infected mothers, potentially causing severe systemic infection with involvement of multiple organs including the lungs, liver, adrenals, and central nervous system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeonatal herpes infection is a serious concern and may present as a mild infection or, more commonly, as a fulminating disease with generalised lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly, and necrotic foci throughout multiple organs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Genital herpes is more commonly caused by herpes simplex virus type 2 (HSV-2) than herpes simplex virus type 1 (HSV-1).","Genital herpes presents as vesicles on genital mucous membranes and external genitalia that rapidly convert to superficial ulcerations with inflammatory infiltrate.","Neonatal herpes infection can occur during passage through the birth canal of infected mothers and often presents as a severe systemic infection."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 354-355."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79980"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20820"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79980"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T12:58:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:02:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13695"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97365"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12497"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Sexually transmitted infections (STI)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-21T20:05:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-21T20:05:58+10:30"},"rel